SIMPLE: ticket
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ticket
<hw>Tick"et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧tiquette</ets> a label, ticket, fr. OF.
<ets>estiquette</ets>, or OF. <ets>etiquet</ets>, <ets>estiquet</ets>;
both of Teutonic origin, and akin to E. <ets>stick</ets>. See
<er>Stick</er>, <pos>n.</pos> & <pos>v.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Etiquette</er>, <er>Tick</er> credit.]</ety> <def>A small piece of
paper, cardboard, or the like, serving as a notice, certificate, or
distinguishing token of something.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>A little note or notice.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Local]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He constantly read his lectures twice a week for above forty
years, giving notice of the time to his auditors in a <qex>ticket</qex>
on the school doors.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A tradesman's bill or account.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Hence the phrase <xex>on ticket</xex>, on account;
whence, by abbreviation, came the phrase <xex>on tick</xex>. See 1st
<er>Tick</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your courtier is mad to take up silks and velvets⟦br⟧
<qex>On ticket</qex> for his mistress.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Cotgrave.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>A certificate or token of right of admission to a
place of assembly, or of passage in a public conveyance; <as>as, a
theater <ex>ticket</ex>; a railroad or steamboat
<ex>ticket</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>A label to show the character or price of
goods.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <def>A certificate or token of a share in a lottery or
other scheme for distributing money, goods, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(f)</sd> <fld>(Politics)</fld> <def>A printed list of candidates
to be voted for at an election; a set of nominations by one party for
election; a ballot.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The old <qex>ticket</qex> forever! We have it by thirty-four
votes.</q> <rj><qau>Sarah Franklin (1766).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Scratched ticket</b></col>, <cd>a ticket from which the
names of one or more of the candidates are scratched out.</cd> --
<col><b>Split ticket</b></col>, <cd>a ticket representing different
divisions of a party, or containing candidates selected from two or more
parties.</cd> -- <col><b>Straight ticket</b></col>, <cd>a ticket
containing the regular nominations of a party, without change.</cd> --
<col><b>Ticket day</b></col> <fld>(Com.)</fld>, <cd>the day before the
settling or pay day on the stock exchange, when the names of the actual
purchasers are rendered in by one stockbroker to another.</cd>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark> <au>Simmonds.</au> -- <col><b>Ticket of
leave</b></col>, <cd>a license or permit given to a convict, or prisoner
of the crown, to go at large, and to labor for himself before the
expiration of his sentence, subject to certain specific conditions.</cd>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark> <au>Simmonds.</au> -- <col><b>Ticket
porter</b></col>, <cd>a licensed porter wearing a badge by which he may
be identified.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ticket</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ticket
<hw>Tick"et</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Ticketed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ticketing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To distinguish by a
ticket; to put a ticket on; <as>as, to <ex>ticket</ex>
goods</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To furnish with a tickets; to book; <as>as, to
<ex>ticket</ex> passengers to California</as>.</def> <mark>[U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- Ticketed. having a ticket, esp. a ticket for travel on a carrier
sucha as an airline. A term used to distinguish those who have made a
reservation for travel, but have not yet paid and received their ticket,
from those who have. "You have a reservation, but you have not yet been
ticketed." -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ticketing</ent>⟦br⟧
